KITCHEN COOL // With both modern and traditional elements incorporated, our goal was to create a space that is both aesthetically pleasing and comfortable to live in.

There is a harmonious synergy between light and dark, warm and cool - the custom handmade brass hood and rich marble countertop create a visual sensory experience.

Our clients fell in love with this beautiful blue/grey Ilve 60" range and we anchored it with skinny shaker white oak cabinets and floating shelves. There is just enough color to give the space depth, but still feel neutral and clean due to the overall openness and subtle colors throughout.

The result is a completely personalized kitchen ready for tasty meals and making memories! 🤍✨

Warm it up…and slow it down…⁠
⁠
The months of January and February are perfect for cocooning at home and cuddling by a warm fire. Comfortable seating adorned with minimal decor invites you to curl up right next to the fire for a nightcap, to read a book or to just watch the flames dance.⁠
⁠
Tip: When placing furniture near a fireplace, you should always place chairs as close to it as it is safe for them to be. This makes the fireplace a central feature of the room's design and attracts people toward it so that it becomes part of the overall ambience.⁠
⁠

Embrace the existing features: Look for ways to celebrate and enhance the existing architectural features of the space, such as moldings, arches, or unique window shapes.⁠
⁠
Take inspiration from the surroundings: Consider the surrounding environment and use it as inspiration for your design. For example, if your space has a beautiful view, make sure to incorporate it into the design.⁠
⁠
Don't be afraid to mix styles: Mixing different design styles can create a visually interesting and unique space. However, it's important to balance the different styles and make sure they work together harmoniously.⁠

TOUCH is more than just a sense, it's a feeling that evokes emotion and transforms spaces. Like the warmth of a fireplace, the coolness of marble, or rough-hewn wooden tables. It's the texture that makes us want to reach out and touch, to connect with the world around us in a deeper way. And in interior design, it's the detail that elevates a space from good to great. So let's embrace the power of touch, and create spaces that not only look beautiful but feel it too.

TASTE - Designing an interior environment is all about realizing a space's intention and engaging the user. You can accomplish this by designing spaces that activate each sense: sight, sound, touch, smell, and taste.⁠
⁠
Why is it important? Despite our tendency to think of our senses as separate entities, they actually work together. Our connection to a moment, an object, a space is stronger the more senses we engage. As a result, design is evolving to incorporate sensory experiences into living and working environments.⁠
⁠
The sense of smell and taste is at the heart of every kitchen. Think about how much time you spend in the kitchen, how often you entertain, if there are comfortable places to sit down, etc. The environment you live in also affects the way you experience drinks and meals. After all, aren't freshly baked cookies (or a well-crafted drink!) more enjoyable in a well-designed kitchen?! 😉⁠

SIGHT - There is a direct link between design and our senses...our moods, emotions, and behavior, whether we feel calm or chaotic.⁠
⁠
This week, we’re sharing how the five senses affect us in design. By creating a sensory reaction, and an all-immersive experience you can evoke a particular feeling, such as coziness, comfort, calm, or engagement, by utilizing all five senses. ⁠
⁠
How do you perceive your spaces...how do you see them? Do they make you happy and feel good, or do they make you feel overwhelmed and restless? We must understand the visual sense of sight in order to create realistic, aesthetically pleasing designs. #visualsense⁠

SMELL - Our emotions can be profoundly affected by aromas. Our senses can be soothed, awakened, and even comforted by certain scents.⁠ ⁠
⁠
Emotion, memory, and smell are closely related, and scent has a powerful impact on the mood and ambiance of interior spaces. We consider scent as carefully as paint color, lighting, and furniture placement in our design plans. Aromatherapy can be used to evoke specific emotions in different rooms, such as relaxing lavender in a bedroom and refreshing orange in a kitchen.⁠
⁠
Make your spaces feel more inviting and cozy by adding home fragrances like fresh florals, candles, diffusers, and sachets. My personal favorite candle scents are sea salt and grapefruit…an uplifting breath of fresh air…(𝘴𝘵𝘢𝘺 𝘵𝘶𝘯𝘦𝘥 𝘧𝘰𝘳 𝘰𝘶𝘳 𝘴𝘪𝘨𝘯𝘢𝘵𝘶𝘳𝘦 𝘴𝘤𝘦𝘯𝘵). 😉⁠

SOUND - Have you ever experienced a moment of déjà vu when the first few bars of a song on the radio evoke an unexpected emotion or call back a distant memory? 🎶⁠
⁠
Whether it's the sounds of nature, the crackling of a fire, the nostalgia of a vintage record player, meditative moments or your favorite playlist...sound enhances your surroundings, and makes your space more inviting and comfortable. 🏡⁠

Choosing the right tiles for your home is an important decision since it can affect the overall look and feel of your living space. I love sourcing for projects at Ann Sacks as they have a wide range of high-quality tiles for both residential and commercial spaces and offer unique and innovative designs. @annsacks_orangecounty @annsacks @socoandtheocmix⁠

Here are 5 tips to consider when selecting tiles for your home:⁠
⁠
1. Determine the purpose of the room: Different rooms in your home will have different functions and therefore, require different types of tiles. For example, a bathroom or kitchen may require tiles that are slip-resistant and easy to clean, while a living room may benefit from tiles that are more decorative and comfortable to walk on.⁠
⁠
2. Consider the style of your home: The tiles you choose should complement the overall style of your home. If you have a modern or minimalist interior, you may want to consider sleek and simple tiles, while a more traditional interior may benefit from patterned or textured tiles.⁠
⁠
3. Think about the color scheme: The color of your tiles can have a big impact on the overall feel of a room. Lighter colors can make a room feel more spacious and open, while darker colors can create a more cozy and intimate atmosphere.⁠
⁠
4. Determine your budget: Tile prices can vary widely, so it's important to determine your budget before making a selection. Keep in mind that more expensive tiles may be more durable and long-lasting, which can save you money in the long run.⁠
⁠
5. Consider the size of the room: The size of the tiles you choose can also affect the look and feel of a room. Larger tiles can make a small room feel more spacious, while smaller tiles can add texture and detail to a larger room.⁠
⁠
Overall, the key is to choose tiles that are both functional and aesthetically pleasing to create a cohesive and inviting living space.⁠

There are a lot of questions I get asked about styling...whether it's a coffee table, a book shelf, and in this case kitchen shelving. Styling begins the dance of cohesive harmony and brings everything together. Here are a few helpful tips:⁠
⁠
1. Start with a clean slate: Remove everything from the shelves.⁠
⁠
2. Choose a color scheme: Pick a color scheme that complements the rest of your kitchen.⁠
⁠
3. Play with patterns: You can add visual interest to your space by mixing and matching different patterns in your decor. Just be sure to keep the color scheme consistent.⁠
⁠
4. Keep it clutter-free: Avoid over-decorating the room and instead, aim for a clean and minimalist look.⁠
⁠
5. Mix and match textures: Play with textures to add interest to your shelf. Mix items like wood cutting boards, glass jars, and metal baskets.⁠
⁠
6. Vary the heights: Group items of varying heights to create visual interest. Use items like cake stands or risers to add height to smaller items.⁠
⁠
7. Use practical items: Don't be afraid to use practical items as decor. Display beautiful plates or colorful bowls that can also be used for serving.⁠
⁠
8. Group items in odd numbers: Grouping items in odd numbers creates a more visually appealing display.⁠
⁠
9. Take a step back: After you've styled your shelf, take a step back and evaluate. Make adjustments as necessary to achieve the heights to create visual interest. ⁠
⁠
10. Keep it simple: Remember that less is often more. Too many objects can clutter a space and make it feel overwhelming. Instead, focus on a few key pieces and let them shine on their own.⁠
⁠
By following these tips, you can create a beautifully styled space that reflects your personality and style. 🤍⁠

The bedroom...the most important room in the house - it's where we let go of the days stressors and rejuvenate, rest and dream. When designing your sanctuary consider the following tips for a peaceful bedroom. 🛌⁠
⁠
- Choose relaxing colors. Soft, muted colors like blues, greens, and grays can help create a calming atmosphere. ⁠
⁠
- Invest in quality bedding. Look for bedding made from natural, breathable materials like cotton or linen, and choose soft, comfortable sheets and pillows.⁠
⁠
- Keep it clutter-free. A cluttered bedroom can make you feel stressed and anxious. Keep the space tidy by putting things away and minimizing the amount of clutter.⁠
⁠
- Bring in plants. Indoor plants can help purify the air and create a more relaxing environment.⁠
⁠
- Maximize natural light. Open up the windows to let in natural light during the day and use blackout curtains to keep the room dark at night.⁠
⁠
- Use soothing scents. Essential oils or candles with calming scents like lavender or chamomile can be a nice addition to the room.⁠
⁠
- Minimize electronics (a tough one! 😉). Try to avoid having electronics in the bedroom, or at least turn them off before bedtime to create a more peaceful environment.⁠

MOVEMENT + RHYTHM. Flowing through a space, its functionality, and how it is used by people are crucial factors. If there is poor flow of movement, even the most beautiful space will fail to achieve the ultimate goal, which is harmony.

WHAT’S NEEDED
In order to create a successful space, a good floor plan is essential! In addition to a good floor plan, a good furniture layout is equally important. It is imperative to consider negative space and positive space when designing furniture layouts to ensure a good flow of movement.

THE BIG PICTURE
Interior design is not just about beautiful tangible furniture and decor. It is also about non-tangible feelings. “The heart of interior design is people.” Feeling joyful in a space should be a seamless experience. Successful spaces are sublime…sometimes for reasons we can't even explain.

Orin Swift Cellars dates back to 1995 when David Swift Phinney went to Florence, Italy for a semester to study abroad. In that time, he learned how wine was made and got hooked. Following a few more years of university, I secured a temporary harvest job at Robert Mondavi Winery in 1997. Orin Swift Cellars was founded in 1998 when he decided that if he was going to work so hard, he should do it for himself. Orin is his father's middle name and Swift is his mother's maiden name. With two tons of zinfandel and not much else, he spent the next decade making wine for others and himself and grew the brand to what it is today.⁠
⁠
The world of wine goes beyond sipping a nice glass of wine; it's also about building a community, making a difference and giving back through shared passions. This Equinox 2020 curation stole my heart with its thumbprint packaging in honor of the heroes who stood strong after the Napa Valley fires. Each bottle serves as a touching reminder of resilience and unity. 🫶⁠
⁠
Vineyards to bottle, Orin Swift Winery weaves tales that transport you to the heart of their passion. Every shipment is an art piece and every sip reflects their commitment to artistry and community.⁠
⁠
Cheers to creating memories and raising a glass to life's extraordinary moments with community, art, and exceptional wine! 🍷⁠

TRANSFORMATIVE. It never ceases to amaze me how powerful it is to renew a space. Here are some not too shabby iPhone photos of our Santiago project in Huntington Beach, CA. ⁠
⁠
We changed the handrail on the stairs, leveled the floor in the living room, and updated the wood flooring, plastered all the walls, changed lighting and window treatments, updated the finish on the fireplace wall in the family room, added wallpaper behind the shelves and installed new hardware. Designed custom sofas and ottoman for the living and family rooms - what a difference! 🙌⁠
⁠
Our living spaces greatly influence our mood. Lighting, natural and manmade materials, colors, acoustics, texture, furniture layout, even living elements affect senses. In the ebb and flow of our daily routines, finding a moment to simply pause often feels like a distant dream. But, as I’ve journeyed through both life and the world of design, I’ve learned that these pauses are not just a luxury; they’re essential to our well-being.

At Laura Brophy Interiors, we believe in the power of anticipation – the joy found not just in the destination but in the journey itself. Whether it’s planning a serene getaway or looking forward to a cherished gathering, it’s these moments of anticipation that weave richness into our lives.

Recently, Rob and I embraced this philosophy, planning a simple, yet meaningful, weekend escape. It wasn’t about grandeur; it was about the change of pace and the excitement that built up to it. This experience was a poignant reminder that sometimes, the act of anticipating joy is a celebration in itself.

So, I encourage you to carve out those moments for yourself. They don’t have to be elaborate; their beauty lies in their significance to you. Let this anticipation be a gentle reminder that between life’s busy chapters, there are serene moments waiting to be savored.
